  "Idea": "The core challenge in visually-rich document understanding lies not only in identifying entities across cells but also in correctly interpreting complex semantic units contained *within* individual cells. Traditional models tokenize text uniformly and apply self-attention globally, often fragmenting multi-word expressions that belong together semantically—especially problematic in tables or forms where cells may contain compound names, addresses, or technical terms. This fragmentation leads to poor entity boundary detection and reduced downstream performance. To address this, we propose a novel framework called 'Layout-Guided Intra-Cell Semantic Unit Discovery via Hierarchical Token Aggregation' (LISA), which introduces a differentiable, hierarchical token merging module that operates within the confines of each cell, guided by both spatial layout and contextual embeddings. LISA first segments input documents into atomic tokens (words/subwords) and associates each with its bounding box coordinates. Within each cell, it applies a bottom-up clustering mechanism that evaluates pairwise mergeability scores between adjacent tokens using a fusion of geometric features (e.g., horizontal distance, alignment, font consistency) and semantic similarity (via contextual embeddings). These scores are computed through a lightweight gating network inspired by Highway Transformers, enabling selective propagation of important representations during merging. The process iteratively combines the most likely token pairs into higher-level units until convergence, forming a tree-structured representation per cell. These aggregated units then serve as enhanced inputs to a downstream Transformer-based model (e.g., LayoutLMv3), replacing flat token sequences with semantically enriched, variable-length super-tokens. Crucially, the entire process is end-to-end trainable via reinforcement learning or surrogate gradient techniques, allowing the model to learn optimal aggregation strategies directly from task-specific objectives like entity recognition F1-score. By preserving cell-level integrity while enhancing internal semantic coherence, LISA enables more accurate identification of multi-word entities, improves robustness to OCR noise, and reduces over-segmentation errors. This approach has broad implications for financial reports, medical records, and legal contracts, where precise interpretation of intra-cell content is essential. Moreover, unlike prior work focusing on global structure (e.g., hypergraphs or concept hierarchies), LISA targets an overlooked micro-level problem with macro-level impact.",
