Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The original LISA idea presents a compelling solution to an underexplored micro-architectural challenge in document understanding—preserving semantic coherence within individual cells by leveraging layout and context for hierarchical token merging. While HGA (Paper 1) improves global structure modeling via hypergraphs, it still operates on pre-segmented tokens and does not resolve intra-cell fragmentation. Similarly, Highway Transformers (Paper 3) introduce gating mechanisms that modulate information flow but are applied globally rather than locally within structural units like cells. My intuition is that the next leap lies not just in *aggregating* tokens hierarchically, but in making this process *context-aware at multiple granularities*—not only within a cell but also informed by its *inter-cell relational context*. That is, whether two words should be merged into a single semantic unit inside a cell may depend not only on their internal layout and semantics but also on how similar aggregations behave in structurally analogous cells across the document (e.g., all “Address” fields follow a consistent phrasing pattern). This introduces a novel duality: local intra-cell aggregation guided by global cross-cell consistency patterns. To achieve this, I propose enhancing LISA with a **cross-cell prototype memory network** that learns reusable templates of common multi-word semantic units (e.g., "John Doe", "New York, NY") and their associated layout-semantic signatures. These prototypes act as soft priors during intra-cell merging, enabling the model to recognize recurring compound entities more robustly—even under OCR noise or partial visibility. Furthermore, instead of relying solely on reinforcement learning for end-to-end training, I integrate a contrastive objective that aligns semantically equivalent but lexically diverse units (e.g., "Dr. A. Patel" vs. "Alice Patel, MD"), improving generalization. This approach shifts from purely bottom-up token merging to a hybrid **memory-augmented, top-down-informed bottom-up aggregation**, creating a feedback loop between local perception and global knowledge. Unlike Navigation.ai (Paper 2), which builds human-interpretable hierarchies externally, our method embeds interpretable, learnable prototypes directly into the model’s reasoning pipeline. This design preserves LISA’s strengths while adding cross-instance generalization, interpretability through prototype visualization, and improved data efficiency.

