  "Idea": "While recent advances in visually-rich document understanding have focused on modeling inter-cell relationships using graph structures or attention over spatial layouts, a critical bottleneck remains in accurately parsing the internal composition of individual cells—particularly when they contain multi-word semantic units such as names, addresses, or technical phrases. Existing models, including LayoutLMv3 and even hypergraph-based extensions like HGA, treat each token independently within a flat sequence, leading to boundary detection errors when entities span multiple subwords or words without clear delimiters. Although LISA introduced a promising direction via hierarchical token merging guided by layout and context, it operates in isolation per cell, missing opportunities for cross-document generalization. We propose a significant evolution: 'Memory-Augmented Layout-Guided Intra-Cell Semantic Unit Discovery' (M-LISA), a framework that enhances hierarchical token aggregation through a dynamic prototype memory bank encoding recurring patterns of semantically coherent units across documents. M-LISA first performs fine-grained token segmentation with bounding box annotations, then applies a differentiable, layout-sensitive merging module within each cell, as in LISA. However, crucially, at each merge step, the model queries a learnable memory matrix populated with prototypes of known semantic units (e.g., person names, dates, monetary amounts) derived from prior observations. Each prototype stores a joint embedding of typical textual content (via averaged contextual representations), expected spatial configuration (e.g., uniform font, left-aligned, consistent spacing), and syntactic role (e.g., header, value). Using soft attention over this memory, M-LISA retrieves relevant templates and uses them to modulate the mergeability scores between adjacent tokens—effectively biasing the system toward forming units that match known, high-confidence patterns. The memory is updated online via exponential moving averages during training, allowing adaptation to domain-specific formats (e.g., invoice line items). Moreover, we introduce a contrastive loss that encourages invariant representations for semantically equivalent units across variations in formatting or morphology, further strengthening generalization. This creates a dual-path architecture: a bottom-up clustering process informed by top-down memory guidance. The resulting super-tokens are fed into a Transformer backbone (e.g., LayoutLMv3) for downstream tasks like entity recognition. Because the memory is differentiable and trained end-to-end, the entire system co-adapts both the merging strategy and the prototype representations. M-LISA enables not only better accuracy in detecting complex intra-cell entities but also offers interpretability—users can inspect which prototypes were activated during inference. It excels in low-resource settings where repeated structural motifs exist, such as standardized forms or regulatory filings. By integrating memory-augmented reasoning into the micro-level token fusion process, M-LISA bridges the gap between local perception and global structural regularity, advancing the frontier of fine-grained document intelligence.",
